For each required `data_modality`, supply rows for {= compression_entity_product =}+ named commercial entity/product pairs whose public materials present genuinely lossless data compression as a core capability for that modality or a closely matching workload. For each pair, cover each of the {= provenance_facet =} provenance facets below with a public source (i.e. {= url =}+ URL per facet).

The entity should be a startup, growth company, commercial lab, product company, or commercially operated project/product family. The product/project should name the specific compression product, platform, service, SDK, hardware IP core, commercial technology, or product family carrying the public claim. Do not use a standalone academic author group, standards committee, generic file format, general-purpose algorithm, bare open-source reference implementation, package registry entry, or repository-only project unless the cited source also identifies a commercial entity or institution-backed product owner. Keep the work to public provenance: cite what sources state about the claim, target, or signal, without deciding whether the compression works, which product is best, or whether anyone should buy, fund, contact, or adopt it.

`data_modality` values:
- `genomics_sequence_data`: sequencing, FASTQ/BAM/CRAM, genomic archives, or comparable biological sequence data.
- `scientific_arrays_columnar_data`: numerical arrays, scientific data containers, columnar analytics, tables, or structured data blocks.
- `sensor_iot_telemetry`: industrial/IoT/robotics/vehicle/sensor telemetry and edge-generated signals.
- `earth_observation_imagery`: satellite, aerial, hyperspectral, geospatial raster, or remote-sensing imagery.
- `medical_raw_imaging`: clinical, microscopy, pathology, radiology, DICOM, or raw biomedical image data.
- `database_storage_data`: database, storage-engine, backup, data-center, warehouse, lakehouse, or enterprise storage payloads.
- `industrial_time_series`: industrial time series, machine logs, operational telemetry histories, energy/utility streams, or observability metrics.
- `model_weights_tensors`: neural-network weights, tensors, embeddings, checkpoints, or ML model artifacts.
- `blockchain_ledger_data`: blockchain, ledger, transaction, state, proof, or archival node data.
- `hardware_ip_core`: FPGA/ASIC/IP-core or embedded-hardware compression blocks tied to a concrete data path.

`provenance_facet` values:
- `lossless_basis`: a company-controlled or product-controlled source-stated fidelity basis for genuinely lossless, reversible, bit-exact, exact-reconstruction, fully lossless, or mathematically lossless compression.
- `target_data_or_use_case`: a company-controlled or product-controlled source-stated tie between the entity/product and the submitted `data_modality`, using a named data type, workload, domain, file family, device/source class, or deployment context. Generic "general-purpose", "real-time", "file archiver", implementation language, broad platform support, or "data compression" wording is not enough.
- `public_technical_signal`: a concrete public technical, deployment, standards, patent, paper, customer, conference, benchmark-listing, reputable technical article, separate technical document, or comparable signal about the commercial entity/product. A bare public repository, README, generic project homepage, package index page, or same page already used only to establish losslessness is not enough by itself.

Sources should be fully public, accessible, and usable. Startup directories, company databases, broad market maps, search result pages, shallow listicles, press-wire mirrors, generic "top compression companies" pages, standalone standards pages, and academic papers about author-named algorithms are not enough by themselves. A page may report benchmark ratios or deployment claims only as public provenance, not as endorsed performance or quality evidence.

Requirements:
- The page must clearly identify the named entity and product/project, or identify an unambiguous product family owned or maintained by the named entity.
- The page must establish commercial entity/product provenance: a real company, startup, commercial lab, product company, or commercially operated project owns, sells, maintains, licenses, deploys, or productizes the named compression offering. Academic author labels, standards bodies, generic algorithms/formats, package names, and repo-only projects do not satisfy this requirement by themselves.
- The page should make its facet-appropriate source role visible. For `lossless_basis`, the page should be an official company/product page, product documentation, company technical blog, company white paper, company-owned repository, patent, or comparable company-tied technical source that directly carries the fidelity claim. For `target_data_or_use_case`, the page should visibly connect the commercial entity/product to the submitted `data_modality`, not merely to compression in general. For `public_technical_signal`, the page should be a concrete technical, deployment, standards, patent, paper, customer, conference, benchmark-listing, reputable technical/news source, or separate technical artifact tied to the commercial entity/product; a bare repository/README is insufficient unless the cited excerpts name an additional public artifact or deployment/standard/benchmark signal beyond repository existence.
- The page should expose a focused source-stated finding for the selected facet. `lossless_basis` needs genuinely lossless or exact-reconstruction wording; visually lossless, near-lossless, error-bounded lossy, vague "no quality loss" claims, and non-compression uses of "lossless" do not satisfy that facet. `target_data_or_use_case` needs a named data type or domain aligned with the submitted modality, such as FASTQ/BAM for genomics, hyperspectral rasters for earth observation, IoT telemetry, model weights, scientific arrays, database/storage payloads, industrial time series, blockchain state, raw imaging, hardware data paths, or a similarly concrete target. `public_technical_signal` needs a concrete public artifact or signal tied to the commercial entity/product, while avoiding ranking, procurement, investment, outreach, or performance-endorsement conclusions.
- The three facet rows for an entity/product should normally require distinct evidence roles. Reusing one URL across facets is acceptable only when the excerpts show three separate, facet-specific findings and the page is a commercial product/source page rich enough to carry all three roles. Repeating a generic project tagline, README summary, paper abstract, standards summary, package metadata, or repository metadata across facets should fail at least the commercial-provenance, target/use-case, or public-signal requirement.
